lish: metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of barley, from Middle English <i>barli</i>, <i>barlich</i> ‘barley’ (Old English <i>bærlic</i>, originally an adjective derivative of <i>bær</i> ‘barley’, a byform of <i>bere</i>).","Americanized form of South German   Behrle   or of its Swiss German cognates <b>Beerli</b>, <b>Berli</b>, or <b>Berly</b>, and probably also of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Berley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Behrle","meanings":["South German (Württemberg): from a pet form of   Behr   ‘bear’, including from a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with Old High German <i>bero</i> ‘bear’.","Altered form of Norwegian <b>Berle</b>: habitational name from a farmstead in the county of Sogn og Fjordane, so named with Old Norse <i>barth</i> ‘rim, edge’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Barley was born in 1380, in Almondbury, Yorkshire, England, her father, Thomas Barley, was 35 and her mother, Isabel Woodhall, was 31. She married John Drakes in 1396, in Huddersfield, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1399, in Thornhill, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1380–after 1399":"1380–pärast 1399","1380–1399":"1380–1399","–Female":"Surnud","1367–1410":"1367–1410","1400–1475":"1400–1475","1399–Male":"1399–Surnud","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1349":"1349","1379":"1379","Abt 1399":"umbes 1399","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1367":"1367","1410":"1410","1399":"1399","1475":"1475","about 1400":"umbes 1400","after 1399":"pärast 1399","Almondbury, Yorkshire, England":"Almondbury, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Woodsome Hall, Huddersfield, West Yorkshire, England":"Huddersfield, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of,, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1380–after 1399":"1380–1399 jälkeen","1380–1399":"1380–1399","–Female":"Kuollut","1367–1410":"1367–1410","1400–1475":"1400–1475","1399–Male":"1399–Kuollut","1400–1440":"1400–1440","134